<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFFFFFCD6BC75810FC98FD6B" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFFFFFCD6BC75810FC98FD6B" blockId="4.[192,1440,512,761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6BC75810FEB2FD8B" bold="true" box="[192,335,512,536]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females of this species group are identified by a unique combination of characters: head unarmed posterolaterally; mesonotum rounded laterally, lacking longitudinal medial carina; scutellar scale distinct, connected to anterior transverse carina; apex of middle and hind femora truncate; 
<collectionCode id="D6F2C089FFFFFFCD6E875851FA6FFDCA" box="[1408,1426,577,601]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T</collectionCode>
2 having four integumental spots; gena carinate; pygidium broadly ovate. Males can be diagnosed by having the parameres conspicuously sinuous, with an isolated medial tuft of long setae ventrally; cuspis virtually straight and overall asetose, except for a small tuft of short setae apically. External characters include white meso- and metatibial spurs, truncate axilla, mesopleuron with blunt tubercle; hypopygium trapezoidal and 
<collectionCode id="D6F2C089FFFFFFCD6A8058F1FE67FD6A" box="[391,410,737,761]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T</collectionCode>
3–5 entirely clothed with white setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFFFFFCD6BC75901FC0BFCBA" box="[192,1014,785,809]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFFFFFCD6BC75901FC0BFCBA" blockId="4.[192,1014,785,809]" box="[192,1014,785,809]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6BC75901FE65FCBA" bold="true" box="[192,408,785,809]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Included taxon.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFFFFFCD6A985901FC0EFCBA" authority="(Gerstaecker, 1874)" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[415,1011,785,809]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6A985901FD0AFCBA" box="[415,759,785,809]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla vitelligera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D47225BDFFFFFFCD68005901FC17FCBA" author="Gerstaecker, A." box="[775,1002,785,809]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="299 - 328" refId="ref18911" refString="Gerstaecker, A. 1874. Mutillarum Americae meridionalis indigenarum synopsis systematica et synonymica. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 40 (1): 41 - 77, 299 - 328." type="journal article" year="1874">Gerstaecker, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFFFFFCD6BC75951FB6CFCEA" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFFFFFCD6BC75951FB6CFCEA" blockId="4.[192,1440,833,889]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6BC75951FE8EFCCA" bold="true" box="[192,371,833,857]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFFFFFCD6A7D5951FD2FFCCA" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[378,722,833,857]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6A7D5951FD2FFCCA" box="[378,722,833,857]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla vitelligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recorded from six South American countries, but we have seen specimens only from semiarid regions of 
<collectingCountry id="C8F418DCFFFFFFCD685B5971FC38FCEA" box="[860,965,865,889]" name="Ecuador" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="C8F418DCFFFFFFCD68D65972FBF1FCEA" box="[977,1036,866,889]" name="Peru" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Peru</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="C8F418DCFFFFFFCD6F4F5971FB70FCEA" box="[1096,1165,865,889]" name="Chile" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Chile</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFFFFFCD6BC75981FE9DFB39" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFFFFFCD6BC75981FE9DFB39" blockId="4.[192,1440,913,1194]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6BC75981FEBFFC3A" bold="true" box="[192,322,913,937]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Remarks.</emphasis>
The vitelligera group is one of the three species groups of 
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD68E85981FB3EFC3A" box="[1007,1219,913,937]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla</emphasis>
with only one species, 
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFFFFFCD6BFC59A2FD72FC5A" authority="(Gerstaecker, 1874)" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[251,655,945,969]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6BFC59A2FE6BFC5A" box="[251,406,945,969]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T. vitelligera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D47225BDFFFFFFCD6AA259A1FD7AFC5A" author="Gerstaecker, A." box="[421,647,945,969]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="299 - 328" refId="ref18911" refString="Gerstaecker, A. 1874. Mutillarum Americae meridionalis indigenarum synopsis systematica et synonymica. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 40 (1): 41 - 77, 299 - 328." type="journal article" year="1874">Gerstaecker, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. As in 
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFFFFFCD69D959A2FB9AFC5A" authority="(Gerstaecker, 1874)" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[734,1127,945,969]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diabolica">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD69D959A2FC92FC5A" box="[734,879,945,969]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T. diabolica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D47225BDFFFFFFCD687A59A1FBA3FC5A" author="Gerstaecker, A." box="[893,1118,945,969]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="299 - 328" refId="ref18911" refString="Gerstaecker, A. 1874. Mutillarum Americae meridionalis indigenarum synopsis systematica et synonymica. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 40 (1): 41 - 77, 299 - 328." type="journal article" year="1874">Gerstaecker, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the mesosomal sculpture of 
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFFFFFCD6BDB59C2FE8BFC7A" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[220,374,977,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6BDB59C2FE8BFC7A" box="[220,374,977,1001]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T. vitelligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other large-bodied 
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD69F359C1FC37FC7A" box="[756,970,977,1001]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla</emphasis>
by lacking the distinctive structures of the more diverse, large-bodied species groups [medial longitudinal mesonotal carina (indica), bilobate anterior transverse carina separated from scutellar scale (juvenilis), and lateral mesonotal tubercles (quadrinotata)]. The 
<typeStatus id="6F58E6EEFFFFFFCD6AC25E22FDCEFBD9" box="[453,563,1074,1098]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="77E323CFFFFFFFCD695B5E22FD07FBDA" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[604,762,1073,1097]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD695B5E22FD07FBDA" box="[604,762,1073,1097]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T. vitelligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, has a conspicuous scutellar scale connected laterally with its anterolateral carinae, as in many species of the indica group. Additionally, aside from a few species found in northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="C8F418DCFFFFFFCD697C5E62FD0FFB19" box="[635,754,1138,1162]" name="Colombia" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, this is the only species in 
<emphasis id="8297845EFFFFFFCD6F345E61FAF4FB1A" box="[1075,1289,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla</emphasis>
known west of the Andes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
